Research Question 1

Finding the top word occurences

ytcomments <- Corpus(VectorSource(df$comments))

#Transformation is performed using tm_map() function to replace, for example, #special characters from the text. Replacing “/”, “@” and “|” with space:

toSpace <- content_transformer(function (x , pattern ) gsub(pattern, " ", x))
ytcomments <- tm_map(ytcomments, toSpace, "/")
ytcomments <- tm_map(ytcomments, toSpace, "@")
ytcomments <- tm_map(ytcomments, toSpace, "\\|")

# Convert the text to lower case
#docs <- tm_map(docs, content_transformer(tolower))
# Remove numbers
#docs <- tm_map(docs, removeNumbers)
# Remove english common stopwords
#docs <- tm_map(docs, removeWords, stopwords("english"))
# Remove your own stop word
# specify your stopwords as a character vector
#docs <- tm_map(docs, removeWords, c("blabla1", "blabla2")) 
# Remove punctuations
ytcomments <- tm_map(ytcomments, removePunctuation)
# Eliminate extra white spaces
ytcomments <- tm_map(ytcomments, stripWhitespace)
# Text stemming
# docs <- tm_map(docs, stemDocument)

#Term document matrix
dtm <- TermDocumentMatrix(ytcomments)
m <- as.matrix(dtm)
v <- sort(rowSums(m),decreasing=TRUE)
d <- data.frame(word = names(v),freq=v)
head(d, 20)

Wordcloud

Note: 1. words: the words to be plotted 2. freq: their frequencies 3. min.freq: words with frequency below min.freq will not be plotted 4. max.words: maximum number of words to be plotted 5. random.order: plot words in random order. If false, they will be plotted in decreasing frequency 6. rot.per: proportion words with 90 degree rotation (vertical text) 7. colors: color words from least to most frequent. Use, for example, colors =“black” for single color.

set.seed(1234)
wordcloud <- wordcloud(words = d$word, freq = d$freq,
                       min.freq=50, max.words=500, random.order=FALSE,
                       rot.per=0.35, colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"))

Bonus (Plot of comments based on hours)

head(yt_comments)

Extract and convert hours

Summarize (Count or freq)

#h_table <- as.data.frame(table(yt_comments['hours']))
#h_table

# is the same with 

hours_count <- yt_comments %>% 
  group_by(hours) %>% 
  summarise(
    count = n()
  )
hours_count

Plot of comments created based on hours

hours_count %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=hours, y=count, group=1)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  labs(
    x = NULL, y = NULL,
    title = "Frequency of Youtube User Creating Comments",
    subtitle = "Comments counts aggregated by hours",
    caption = "\nSource: Data collected from Youtube's REST API via
    googleapiclient"
  )
